Forms of Assembly: All Things Considered
S 2023 | Liu Yunsong
instructor: Malkit Shoshan













TOPIC OF INTEREST

at the convergence of labor， media， and platform

“Bodies congregate, they move and speak together, and they lay claim to a certain space as public space.”( Butler, Judith. “2. Bodies in Alliance and the Politics of the Street.” (2015). )

The project engages couriers, food delivery guys, gig workers, or giggers, that are, as Jeremy Zallen argues for the categorization of workers, “descriptions of power relations, which meant they were descriptions of inequality.”(Zallen Jeremy. 2019. American Lucifers)

Individuals bear the brunt of deprivation of social reproduction hours inescapably reprogrammed within the “historically situated complex of metabolisms and assemblages.”

The project looks at the assembly of gig economy workers and their patches of livelihood that pale into indifference under the gig economy to form new modes of resistance, with regards to their precarious working conditions, the affective labor, and the Orwellian labor coordination of algorithms.

The gig economy, by definition, is a labor market that relies heavily on temporary and part-time positions filled by independent contractors and freelancers rather than full-time permanent employees. It is prompted for the flexibility of working time and workload by management literature. Pop business book idealizes the subjectivity of gig workers as ‘entrepreneurialism, self-development, malleability, prudence, and communicativeness’ but veil the labor exploitation and precarity. Gig workers have minimal access to labor protection due to the temporality of the work. The objective is to increase the saliency of the “casualization of the workforce, informalization of the formal economy, and the so-called ‘demutualization of risk’” illuminated by Valerio De Stefano concurrent with the gig economy. The project intends to convey an epistemic and normative understanding of gig labor. The writing congregates historical interlocutions on labor, technology, and forms of control. The installation directly responds to the fragmentation of the workspace, isolation of workers, and its debilitating effects on workers’ solidarity and decreasing bargaining power which will be analyzed in detail later. The project also investigates technology that enables labor exploitation to be realized at a renewed intensity.

The project looks at the niche of “work-on-demand via app” in the gig economy, referring to activities that are “channeled online but are executed in the ‘real’ world and locally.” Research of the project focuses on food delivery of online platforms whose intangible coordination gets materialized in the real world through the labor of couriers: circulation of material goods, immaterial labor, and invisible algorithmic control.

Technology, Labor, and the Fragmentation of Labor Workspace

From the perspective of Marx's Historical Materialism, a framework for understanding historical development and social change based on the material conditions of society, particularly the ways in which humans produce and exchange goods and services, technology plays a crucial role in determining the productive forces of society. Relations of production, the human relationships that shape the production process, include all organized relations that contribute to the way the productive forces are deployed. Marx points out that the two changes in the mode of production refer to the innovation of organizational technology and science and technology, respectively. The innovation of platforms greatly contributes to both, which we will discuss after the cursory intellectual lineage outlines.

Cara New Dagget delineates a picture of energy politics and governance in her The Birth of Energy: contrary to Marx’s view of the steam mill leading industrial capitalist Andreas Malm contends that the advantages of coal had more to do with human power than with mechanical power. Steam power owes its prevalence to the replaceability of workers it grants since the factories are no longer restricted to water-proximate areas. Relocation became a solution for untamed workers. Jeremy Zallen, in his American Lucifers, illuminates a lit geography of pushed-back nights in homes, cities, and factories that “consumed energy accumulated by hundreds of thousands of laborers mobilized to work and die in mines, forest camps, farms, factories, ships, and oil wells.” New York sewing women ‘get to work from sunrise to midnight under the Piney lights for survival. Then what changes does the innovation of the platform bring to laborers?

The project applies the same methodology as Zallen’s in American Lucifers, meaning “to properly understand the strange geography of turpentine requires close attention to people and place and work…Only by carefully following the struggles among enslavers, enslaved, and landscapes in time and space can the full contours of resistance, power, and freedom in the camps be seen.” The project starts with the way in which tasks are evaluated and compensated, the type of assignments given, and the methods used to charge fees and provide compensation that differs among different platforms. Food delivery platforms deploy mechanisms that enable the assessment of their workers, which aids in the efficient management and continual evaluation of their workforce. These mechanisms also permit the platforms to exclude "underperforming" workers with fewer order allocations, thereby terminating their employment relationship if they do not maintain a certain level of average ratings. The fear of being replaced forces workers to stay alert 12 hours each day: technology enables the ultimate phase of commodification and consumerism, which involves turning humans into commodities. The use of platforms that grant employers automatic management and supervision is becoming increasingly common in the gig economy. These platforms are designed to outsource the supervision work to customers, allowing employers to save time and money. However, this approach often comes at a cost to gig workers. They are expected to work long hours, often sacrificing their health and personal time to meet the demands of their job. The lack of oversight and support can also lead to unsafe working conditions and the potential for exploitation. More specifically, the use of micromanagement significantly reduces management costs. The equilibrium of management cost and benefit of fragmented working space has been shifted by customers’ review input so that employers could have a fragmented workspace to break the solidarity among workers.

A Closer Look

This project focuses on food delivery workers in China whose presence makes possible the elision of geopolitical distance that is crystallized to power by the digital undercurrent of the urban environment and the flow of capital. It takes into account the job insecurity, working hours, and working conditions of workers in Zhongguancun, Beijing, China.

Zhongguancun is a district in Beijing and one of the first food delivery teams. A postdoc of sociology at Peking University Long Chen worked as an undercover food courier in Zhonguancun and documented his observations in Labor Order under "Digital Control"——Research on Labor Control of Delivery Riders. In his fieldwork and theoretical exploration, he put forth the discrepancy between the promise of “autonomy and freedom” and the labor under “digital control.”

In actuality, algorithms play a significant role in determining the number of orders that each courier receives as well as the distance between destinations. These algorithms take into account various factors, such as past customer reviews and statistics related to the efficiency of each delivery. By analyzing this data, the algorithms are able to make informed decisions that optimize the delivery process and ensure that customers receive their orders in a timely and efficient manner. In essence, the algorithms are designed to help streamline the delivery process and ensure that all parties involved - from the couriers to the customers.

Fieldwork

Labor order under "digital control"*——a study on the labor control of delivery riders. . . Manufacture improved the way labor was organized. On the one hand, the division of labor increases productivity and creates "partial workers"; on the other hand, the labor hierarchy divides workers into skilled and unskilled workers. The division of labor and the hierarchy jointly promote the improvement of production efficiency, but at the same time lead to the depreciation of the value of labor force . . . In "Uber: Algorithms Redefining Work," Alex Rosenblat reveals how Uber uses algorithms to control its users -- drivers. . . Behind all this, Rosenblatt points out, “Uber’s algorithms give the company tremendous control over how drivers work” (Rosenblatt, 2019: 187). . . "Returning to the hidden place of production and exposing the obscured labor process and production scenes to the researchers' vision is the essence of labor research" (Wen Xiang, Zhou Xiao, 2007: 29). . . " It stands to reason that I should send Zhengfang Building first, and then go to Y University Engineering College. But the schedule of the engineering college is tight. If the paper is sent to the Zhengfang Building first, the bill will be overdue by the time of the engineering college. What do you think I should do? I had time to see the Zhengfang Building, so I went to the Engineering College first, which is equivalent to sending the far ones first and then the near ones. Who would have thought that as soon as I arrived at the Institute of Technology, the customers of the Zhengfang Building called me and asked me how I got there. I said I went to the engineering school first, Because this order is going to time out, And kept telling her that I will be at the Zhengfang Building soon, But she didn't sound very happy, and said that it was because she saw me coming from her mobile phone that she kindly went downstairs in advance to save me time. Unexpectedly, I went to another place first, and I was quite embarrassed to let people wait for a while. "[ by Long Chen]

Survey

A survey of 6196 samples conducted by 199it research team and the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences shows workers’ distribution regarding age, education level, recreational activity, monthly income, the channel for seeking help, demand from the government, demand from the employers, and confidence level. Based on the provided data, it seems that the majority of food couriers have completed at least a senior high school education, as indicated by the highest ratio of 0.471 for this education level. Junior high education is the second most common education level among food couriers, with a ratio of 0.24. The technical school has a ratio of 0.168. The ratios for elementary and college education are relatively low at 0.05 and 0.071, respectively. The majority of food couriers fall within the age range of 21-40, with a ratio of 0.881. The age range of 21-30 has the highest ratio of 0.51, indicating that many food couriers are in their early to mid-20s. The age range of 31-40 has a ratio of 0.371, suggesting that a significant number of food couriers are in their 30s. Food couriers face various challenges and negative experiences while on the job. Discrimination is the most commonly reported unhappy thing at work for food couriers, with a ratio of 0.36. Traffic accidents are the second most commonly reported unhappy thing, with a ratio of 0.293. This suggests that food couriers may be at a higher risk of accidents or injuries while on the job due to factors such as long working hours, high pressure to meet delivery times, or challenging road conditions. The third most commonly reported unhappy thing is being scolded by customers, with a ratio of 0.257. This suggests that food couriers may face negative customer interactions, which can impact their job satisfaction and overall mental health.

The survey actualized and contextualized the discussion of gig workers' social and occupational precarity, the absence of legislative protection of this new form of labor, and the structural inequity of social distribution.





















Pillows For Rest And For Assembly

The installation offers a counter-narrative, one that seeks to reassemble workers and rebuild solidarity in the face of these challenges. Through a series of counter-narratives, the installation deconstructs the dominant discourse of management literature and exposes the ways in which it reinforces existing power structures and perpetuates inequality.

Space
At the same time, the installation imagines a new vision of work that emphasizes community and cooperation over competition and individualism. By bringing workers together and facilitating communication and collaboration, the installation offers an antidote to the atomization and fragmentation of the modern workplace as a result of automatic management and supervision. It offers a sustainable and empowering work model that recognizes the dignity and worth of every worker and seeks to build a more just and equitable society.

The physical installation imagines the assembly of people to reconfigure, produce, and reproduce the materiality of that environment. The presence of people and objects gives expression to the politics in what Butler categorized as the “virtual space that is unbound by the architecture of the public square,” in this case, the gig platforms.

The pillows can be arranged to accommodate different forms of assembly, spanning individuals and couples, sitting and lying down.

Time
The installation employs the semantic signification of pillow, a tool for sleep and rest, to lay the statement of labor exploitation and the lack of social reproduction. It is grounded on the commonality of the overly-extended working hours in the current labor market. The installation aims to construct a tacit agreement on a normative labor condition.
